Exposing an OpenShift CRC Application Publicly Using Cloudflare Tunnel + Custom Domain
This guide documents the complete process for exposing an application running on OpenShift CRC to the public internet using Cloudflare Tunnel and a custom domain (e.g., ro-store.com).
It includes Cloudflare setup, DNS configuration, tunnel creation, OpenShift route updates, and CRC DNS fixes.

1. Prerequisites
A running CRC (CodeReady Containers) cluster

An application deployed in OpenShift with a working Route

A Cloudflare account

A domain added to Cloudflare (e.g., ro-store.com)

cloudflared installed on the same machine where CRC runs

Basic knowledge of OpenShift (oc CLI)

2. Install and Authenticate Cloudflared
Install cloudflared and authenticate it with Cloudflare:

sh
cloudflared tunnel login
A browser window opens → log in and authorize Cloudflare.

3. Create a Cloudflare Tunnel
sh
cloudflared tunnel create taskmanager
This generates a credentials file in:

Code
~/.cloudflared/<UUID>.json
Example:

Code
~/.cloudflared/4670d8c5-fcdb-4453-93d6-970102d86ef6.json
4. Create DNS Route for Your Domain
To expose the public domain (https://www.ro-store.com):

sh
cloudflared tunnel route dns taskmanager www.ro-store.com
Cloudflare automatically creates a CNAME pointing to the tunnel.

5. Create the Cloudflare Tunnel Configuration
Create the config file:

sh
nano ~/.cloudflared/config.yml
Add:

yaml
tunnel: taskmanager
credentials-file: /home/redhat/.cloudflared/4670d8c5-fcdb-4453-93d6-970102d86ef6.json

ingress:
  - hostname: www.ro-store.com
    service: http://task-manager.apps-crc.testing
  - service: http_status:404
Replace the credentials file name with your actual JSON file.

6. Fix CRC DNS Resolution (Critical Step)
CRC inside a VM resolves all OpenShift routes to 127.0.0.1.
Cloudflared must be able to reach the OpenShift router.

Edit /etc/hosts:

sh
sudo nano /etc/hosts
Add:

Code
127.0.0.1 router-default.apps-crc.testing
127.0.0.1 task-manager.apps-crc.testing
This ensures Cloudflare Tunnel can reach the OpenShift router.

7. Update the OpenShift Route to Use Your Domain
Your OpenShift Route must match the Cloudflare hostname.

Edit the route:

sh
oc edit route task-manager-frontend -n app1
Set:

yaml
spec:
  host: www.ro-store.com
Save and exit.

8. Start the Cloudflare Tunnel
sh
cloudflared tunnel run taskmanager
You should see:

Code
Connected to Cloudflare
Registered tunnel connection
9. Test the Setup
Test OpenShift router locally:
sh
curl -H "Host: www.ro-store.com" http://router-default.apps-crc.testing
You should receive your frontend HTML or a 404 from your app.

Test public domain:
Code
https://www.ro-store.com
Your application should now be publicly accessible.

10. Optional: Add root domain
sh
cloudflared tunnel route dns taskmanager ro-store.com
Update config.yml:

yaml
  - hostname: www.ro-store.com
    service: http://task-manager.apps-crc.testing
Restart the tunnel.

Final Result
Your CRC OpenShift application is now publicly accessible at:

Code
https://www.ro-store.com
via Cloudflare Tunnel, with full HTTPS, no port forwarding, and no public IP required.